title: For Sale/Trade:  Custom 280 Rem
postcontent:
I have a custom built 280 Remington I recently inherited from my wife's late grandfather. I know from talking to him the gun was built by a gunsmith in Gainsville Tx but other than that I do not know the history. The rifle is built on a Mauser action, has a 3lb crisp trigger pull, a heavy taper barrel and the barrel is free floated.  The muzzle crown is crisp with no damage and the overall bluing is in very good condition. No rust!  As you can see, it has a custom thumb hole walnut stock (he was a huge fan of thumb holes) with a very nice elk carved in the cheek piece. He told me one time he had sighted it in with a box of ammo and took it to the field one time before his health began failing. I cannot swear to the round count but the bore is in excellent condition. 
The scope is what I believe a fist generation Redfield Widefield range estimation scope. The glass is crystal clear and the tube has a couple of wear marks. 
This would make a great long distance blind gun but I don't think you'd want to take it for a hike in the mountains.

title: For Sale:  HSGI Tactical Chest harness/rig with map case. OD- green
postcontent:
Asking $200 for the rig.

This vest is designed to carry a LOT of stuff. It is worn on the chest, with the tradition cross straps in the back. The adjustable shoulder/ back straps have buckles on each side where it can be detached form the vest. It also has an adjustable waist-strap that is removable as well. The left shoulder strap has a D-ring mounted on it. I removed the D-ring from the other side because it hindered a proper shouldering of a weapon.

It has 4 large magazine pouches on the front. These are large enough to hold 3x m16 magazines each. They will also hold smoke grenades, pistols, as well as lots of other magazines in different calibers including ak-47 and .308 mags. There are adjustable velcro straps that can be raised or lowered for taller magazines, and there is also an adjustable bungee-cord type retainment cord that can be tightened or loosened depending on how much retention you want. They can be closed with either velcro, buckles, or neither.

The four magazine pouches are attached to a big map case that takes up the whole front side of the vest. This map case has a see-through plastic case to store a map in. It also has a compass pouch and pen slots as well as an administrative pouch behind that. There  are also velcro linings that, if opened, yield extra storage space within the map pouch. The map case pouch is secured with two zippers and a buckle on the top. There is also a strand of the loop-side velcro that runs horizontally above the mag pouches under the buckle. I have attached two pistol magazine pouches (that open to the right and left) to the velcro.

On each side of the vest are 4 columns and 4 rows of webbing (with a space in-between each row). I will also include at least 1 (2 if I can find the other) Blackhawk large sustainment pouch (OD Green) that fits perfectly on the side webbing of the best. This has a mesh bottom and a zipper along the top. There is also molle (3 colums and 4 rows) on the front of this pouch. This pouch will hold a canteen (and there is plenty of room to spare). 

On each side of the vest, there are also two zippers along the top that open up into the main interior pocket of the vest. This main interior pocket runs the whole length of the vest un-interrupted and can be used to store extra supplies or whatever. 

There are also four plastic points along the bottom of the vest to attach a tactical belt if desired.

The back of the vest (part that touches your chest) is also completely lined with molle.

I have made a few, minor alteration to the vest:
1- the d-ring mentioned above has been removed from the right strap
2- in each magazine pouch, there was a strap separating each magazine. I removed those and burnt off the extra material. Structurally and functionally, it has only been an improvement.

Overall, it is in superb condition. I have only used it at the range a few times. It is not dirty, there are no fraying materials or any part of the vest that is in danger of breaking. Even the alterations I made have been secured with a lighter to where they will not degrade the integrity of the vest. I have had it for a few years, but it mainly sits in my closet as a "go-vest." I bought it to keep lots of mags, water, food, survival equipment, etc in for a bug-out scenario. If you want, it can also be set up to be a good hunting rig with your maps, binos in the sustainment pouch, extra food, etc. Various other tactical applications will work with this vest. It does work with backpacks, but the hip-pads may get in the way of the bottom back strap of the vest.

This is a great buy as it is a basically new vest for a good price. I am selling because I want to buy a smaller rig and apply some of the money I may make to ammo and weapon upgrades.

Please email me/ contact me with any questions you may have! If the pictures I upload do not suffice, I would be happy to send you more, or even a video if you are seriously considering the purchase.

Thanks!

title: For Sale:  ATI 7.62x39 Demil 124GR Russian STL Case New Bullet 500RD
postcontent:
This ammo is corrosive primed, copper washed steel case. This is loose packed ammo counted by weight at the factory so the round count may be more or less 20 rounds

500 rd case - 7.62x39 Russian Surplus de-milled with non-magnetic bullet - range ammo - read description

This ammo was 1970's manufacture Russian surplus imported for a government contract which never worked out and the importer had to de-mil this ammo by removing the steel core bullet and replacing it with a lead core bullet so it could legally be sold to the consumer market. They used a non-magnetic 124 grain Berry's bullet to replace the original steel core projectile. We test fired some of this ammo and the blunter projectile did lead to 1-2 jams per 30 round magazine in a Chinese Mak-90. We do not guarantee that this ammo will feed flawlessly, if you buy this ammo expect some jams and minor feeding issues with some rounds. We have also had the occasional report that this ammo is not as accurate as some of the other types on the market, so do not expect it to be. That said, it is the lowest cost ammo for those of you who are required to use non-magnetic projectiles at your range. This ammo is corrosive primed, copper washed steel case.
